column14:
On February 24, the Swiss Canton Ticino reaffirms the federal list of recommendations of hygienic measures to prevent the spread of the Coronavirus:
-frequent hand washing
- limit touching one's face
- keep distance to sick people
- cough into tissues 
- wear masks only if one is sick
- stay at home in case of flue-symptoms
- avoid health facilities with influenza-like symptoms 
- not take antibiotics, if not prescribed 
- in case of doubt, one should not go to the hospital, but contact the family doctor or call the cantonal or federal hotline

column14: France. On February25, 2020, the City of Lyon formed a strategic and operational supervisory committee for managing the Covid-19 crisis. This committee is operational 7 days a week under the authority of the Mayor of Lyon. On May 11th, 2020, the City of Lyon announced that the strategic and operational supervisory committee will begin working on Lyon's reopening plan.

From 13th March 2020 on, the Swiss Canton of Neuchâtel has been monitoring the health of patients suspected of Covid-19 if they were sent back home by the coronavirus triage centers. The centers' personnel regularly monitors the evolution of the symptoms of each individual through phone calls.

NB: as a reminder, the triage centers decide whether suspect patients should be sent to the hospital or back home, and if they should get tested or not.

On 13th March 2020, the Swiss Canton of Neuchâtel created 7 triage centers to sort suspect patients depending on the seriousness of their symptoms, and decide whether or not they should get tested. Based on several health checks conducted at the centers (fever checks, blood pressure, oxygen saturation tests...), patients are either sent to the hospital or back home. An 8th center managed by Médecins du Monde has also been created to welcome undocumented immigrants and asylum seekers. A telephone line has been opened to book appointments at the centers. This policy overall aims at relieving the congestion in hospitals.

As of March 14, Hesse (Germany) declares that contact with other people outside the members of one's own household should be reduced to the absolute necessary minimum. Being in public places is only permitted alone, with one other person not living in the own household or in the circle of members of the own household. A minimum distance of 1.5 metres must be maintained when meeting other people.

From 9 May onwards it will again be permitted to meet in public with members of another household in addition to those living in their own household.
The Hessian event concept provides for meetings of up to 100 people to be permitted under regulated conditions from 9 May onwards

column14:
On March 17th, the government of Saxony, Germany announced that all non-essential public services are to be kept closed from now on.
Since this announvement was not specified with a clear end date, the government clarified on March 20th which non-essential public services must be closed: among others theatre, cinemas, concert halls and venues, operas, museums, exhibition halls, services in district cultural centres and community centres, open children and youth work services, public libraries, planetariums, zoological exhibitions in closed rooms, offers from adult education centres, language and integration courses offered by integration course providers, offers from music schools, offers from literature houses, offers from public and private educational institutions and playgrounds. This was first limitied to April 20th, it has  been extended until May 3rd. Besides, some exceptions are granted to schools for the purpose of preparing for examinations, universities and vocational academies, specialised libraries and archives, educational institutions for initial and further vocational training and day-care centres for emergency care if hygiene standards are established.

column14:
On March 17th, the government of Saxony, Germany announced that all non-essential public services are to be kept closed from now on.
The government clarified on March 20th which non-essential public services must be closed: among others theatres, cinemas, concert halls and venues, operas, museums, exhibition halls, services in district cultural centres and community centres, open children and youth work services, public libraries, planetariums, zoological exhibitions in closed rooms, offers from adult education centres, language and integration courses offered by integration course providers, offers from music schools, offers from literature houses, offers from public and private educational institutions and playgrounds. This was first limitied to April 20th, it has been extended until May 3rd. Besides, some exceptions have been granted to some facilities that provide certain hygiene concepts. This was once again extended until May 20th. Exceptions were expanded to memorials, libraries, archives, museums, exhibitions, galleries, exhibition houses and outdoor facilities of zoos, botanical and zoological gardens. Their re-opening is also linked to the obligation of ensuring appropriate hygiene concepts.

column14:
On March 17th, the government of Saxony, Germany announced that all non-essential public services are to be kept closed from now on.
The government clarified on March 20th which non-essential public services must be closed: among others theatres, cinemas, concert halls and venues, operas, museums, exhibition halls, services in district cultural centres and community centres, open children and youth work services, public libraries, planetariums, zoological exhibitions in closed rooms, offers from adult education centres, language and integration courses offered by integration course providers, offers from music schools, offers from literature houses, offers from public and private educational institutions and playgrounds. This was first limitied to April 20th, it has been extended until May 3rd. Besides, some exceptions have been granted to some facilities that provide certain hygiene concepts. Starting May 20th, these rules were extended to theatres, musical theatres, cinemas, concert halls, concert venues and opera houses, provided that a hygiene concept approved by the local authority is in place. Offers in literature houses, cabaret venues, socioculture and guided tours are also possible. The conditional re-opening applies also to facilities for specialist counselling in the social and psychosocial field, senior citizens' meeting places and offers of child and youth work, in force until June 5th.

Germany is enforcing a Restriction of Non-Essential Businesses: The Bavarian government has prohibited the operation of all leisure facilities such as swimming baths, cinemas, bars and discotheques, theatres, museums, sports grounds and playgrounds, but also brothels and restaurants of all kinds. Exceptions are company canteens and the serving of take-away food or delivery. It must be ensured that the distance between guests is at least 1.5 metres and that there are no more than 30 people in the rooms. It was also prohibited to open retail shops of any kind, with the exception in particular of food and beverage shops, pharmacies and banks, post offices and online shops.

On 13th March 2020, the Swiss Canton of Neuchâtel ordered the closure of all schools, professional training centers, high schools, universities, "hautes écoles" (specialized higher education institutions) and extra-familial care centers (eg: day-care centers), from 16th March 2020 to 4th April 2020. A minimum extra-familial care service will be however provided on certain conditions to families who can't keep their children at home (conditions: parents work in healthcare or security and have no other child care option). On 16th March 2020, this policy was extended to 19th April 2020 by the federal Ordinance 2 of 16th March 2020, which took over all cantonal measures.

In Switzerland, the state council of the canton Zurich decided that from the 1st of April on additional health workers have to be hired because the outbreak of COVID-19 shows that the cantonal medical service is only able to handle smaller, local exposures but it is not set up for large, nationwide events.
The detailed list is:

-	1.0 positions senior physician, (wage class 22) 
-	1.8 positions Research Associate, (wage class 20) 
-	0.5 positions as an assistant doctor, (wage class 19) 
-	1.0 position administrative secretary, (wage class 12) 

This is a total job increase of 4.3

On March 20th, Lyon published an announcement warning against scammers taking advantage of the Covid-19 pandemic, including those selling hand sanitizer at prices higher than the national fixed price. The city "reminds individuals that there does not currently exist any vaccine, food, air purifier, lamp, dietary supplement, or any other product that protects from or cures COVID 19." The announcement also reminded readers that "COVID 19 tests are carried out by health authorities via medical prescription. No other organization or individual is allowed to process these tests."
The announcement warns that purchasing paracetamol online is illegal, and warns against scams of home decontamination procedures, stating that "no home decontamination procedures are scheduled by the government at this time. Those pretending to carry out a mandatory decontamination are unauthorized to do so and are looking to gain access into unsuspecting peoples' houses."

They are set up until April 20th. The previously set up visiting ban is extended from April 20th to May 3rd. Starting April 20th, a few exceptions can be made for relatives and related persons of people in inpatient care facilities, outpatient assisted living communities for people in need of care, residential groups for people with disabilities and hospices in the Free State of Saxony. Visits to the facility must be limited in time and number of persons and must be specifically coordinated with the facility in advance.

On March 22th, 2020 the government of Saxony announced restrictions upon leaving the house for all state residents. Only with reasonable purpose of shopping, work, child care delivery, medical visits or personal sports leaving the house is allowed. In the last case, gatherings of people are prohibted above the limit of 5 people from the same household (first set until April 5th), it has been extended to April 20th. Besides, compliance was specified by introducing fines for non-compliance. Starting April 20th, leaving the house without reasonable suppose is possible, but only alone or, with people from the same household or with one person not from the same household. Apart from that, the government recommended to refrain from private travels and excursion as well as from visiting relatives until further notice. From May 5th onwards, meeting with a couple from another household, from 
another household (regardless of size) is granted. Exceptions for school children to enable meetings up to four complement this relaxation. 
Starting June 6th, this has been relaxed since private meetings in one's own living environment are allowed. Meetings and gatherings in public space continue to be only permitted alone and with members of one's own household, accompanied by the partner, with persons for whom there is a right of custody or access, and with members of another household or with up to ten other persons. Family celebrations are allowed up to 50 persons (in place until June 29th).

Germany is enforcing a Restriction of Non-Essential Businesses: The Bavarian government has prohibited the operation of all leisure facilities such as swimming baths, cinemas, bars and discotheques, theatres, museums, sports grounds and playgrounds, but also brothels and restaurants of all kinds. Exceptions are company canteens and the serving of take-away food or delivery. It must be ensured that the distance between guests is at least 1.5 metres and that there are no more than 30 people in the rooms. It was also prohibited to open retail shops of any kind, with the exception in particular of food and beverage shops, pharmacies and banks, post offices and online shops.

The catering, hotel and tourism sectors are gradually reopening. Since May 18, outdoor  gastronomies like beer gardens have been reopening. From 25th May , restaurants with indoor areas will be allowed to open again. Hotels, holiday apartments, guesthouses and camping sites can accommodate guests THEREFORE again come May 30th onwards.Tourist attractions such as amusement parks, castles, excursion boats or cable cars will be available from 30th May as well. However, strict regulations apply in all areas, including opening hours, hygiene concepts, limits on the number of guests, and distance requirements.

On 25th March 2020, the Swiss canton of Neuchâtel suspended all statutory time limits for submitting requests for referenda and popular initiatives on cantonal and communal matters. Moreover, the canton suspended the issuance of certificates of eligibility to vote ("attestation de la qualité d'électeur") for each request (i.e. the validation of signatures: the administration double-checks that each person who signed the request is eligible to vote and issues a document certifying the number of eligible people who have signed the request). During this suspension, signatures cannot be collected for a prospective petition (referenda or initiatives). The statutory time limits for processing requests is also suspended. All these measures are set to last until 31st May 2020.

In Switzerland, the canton Aargau decided that the deadline for submitting the tax return 2019 is extended until June 30 for employed people and until September 30, 2020 for self-employed people and farmers.
The deadline for submitting the 2019 tax return for legal entities will be extended until September 30, 2020. There is no need to submit a deadline extension.
For tax claims, a reminder and debt enforcement stop applies until June 30, 2020.
Official deadlines set by the tax authorities for the submission of additional documents can be extended upon request. The tax authorities treat such requests with goodwill.
From March 1, 2020 to December 31, 2020, in the event of late payment of the cantonal and municipal tax due in this period, no default interest is due.

If a company is bankrupt or must close because of corona, a provision can be made in the 2019 annual financial statements.

The Department of Finance and Resources can deviate from legal deadlines in cases of liquidity shortage and difficulties in complying with procedural obligations with the tax law.

column14:
From the 2nd of April on there will be public social assistance prevention measures. Accordingly, the regulations for responsibilities for case management and assistance changed.
If a municipal or regional social service is unable to perform its duties the municipality has to provide a temporary solution. 
If they can’t, the cantonal social service can temporarily transfer responsibility for case management and assistance to another local/ regional social service or another suitable agency.
It takes over the case management and assistance in accordance with the legal requirements applicable in its municipality, if this one is not able to fulfill its duties another appropriate body takes over.
The original municipality has to bear the expenses incurred by the newly responsible institution.
The cantonal social service can take appropriate coordination measures and regulate uniform criteria for assuming responsibility in an instruction.

Requests for the granting of cost credits for medical purposes that do not tolerate a delay are to be treated as appropriate and the associated payments as quickly as possible to do.

The cantonal social service can oblige the municipal and regional social services to take over the management of the case for the duration of the ongoing jurisdictional procedure.

In Switzerland, the canton Aargau decided at the 1st of April that from the 2nd of April on the hospitals are exempted from certain regulations within the scope of fulfilling the special regulation (SonderV 20-1).

To authorize the hospitals for treatment regardless of the hospital list § 8 para. 3 of the ordinance on the hospital list about the barriers and the spectrum of the service orders placed on the hospital list is suspended
Irrespective of the performance mandate, hospitals are authorized to treat patients within their medical area of competence. 
Treatments that are performed outside an assigned performance mandate and within the medical competence area are to be billed based on the Aargau tariff specified by the Department of Health and Social Affairs (DGS) in a specific case. The approved Aargau tariff for early rehabilitation is to be applied for the convalescence departments to be created by rehabilitation clinics.
Based on Section 7 (4) of the hospital list, the Department of Health and Social Affairs can also issue hospitals that do not fulfill the requirements of Section 2 (2) of the hospital list as well as the procedure, the documents and the procedure in accordance with Section 3–5 hospital list. 

To authorize inpatient care facilities to create bed capacity § 13 para. 1 letter b and para. 2 of the Nursing Ordinance (PflV) is suspended.
The § 4 para. 2 letter b of the Care Act (PflG), the guideline value for the proof of need is suspended.

column14: On 13th March 2020, the Swiss Canton of Neuchâtel created 7 triage centers to sort suspect patients depending on the seriousness of their symptoms, and decide whether or not they should get tested. Based on several health checks conducted at the centers (fever checks, blood pressure, oxygen saturation tests...), patients are either sent to the hospital or back home. An 8th center managed by Médecins du Monde has also been created to welcome undocumented immigrants and asylum seekers. A telephone line has been opened to book appointments at the centers. This policy overall aims at relieving the congestion in hospitals. On 15th April 2020, the canton of Neuchâtel reduced the number of triage centers from 8 to 5 in order to match the demand and the resources.

On April 17th, the government of Saxony, Germany, announced that it would strongly recommend to wear a face mask in public, especially when in contact with risk groups. Apart from that recommendation, wearing a face mask in public services and retail businesses is mandatory, first valid from April 20th until May, 3rd. On April 30th, the government announced that the measures will be extended to May 20th.
On May 15th, the recommendations and obligations of wearing a face mask were confirmed until June 5th. The instances of obligation to wear a mask were broadened by adding worship services, funerals, mourning ceremonies and marriage ceremonies as well as driving, flying and boat schools.

The previous recommendation of the government to wear a face mask in public and the obligation to wear it in public services and retail businesses was set until May, 3rd. This was extended to May 20th. Now, it has been extended once more until June 5th. Beyond that, worship services, funerals, mourning ceremonies and marriage ceremonies are permitted if the rules of distance are complied with. Beside providing to maintain a minimum distance of 1.5 metres throughout the meeting, participants must use a mouth-and-nose cover, and it must be ensured that the protection of the rest of the population is respected by maintaining safe distances between the meeting and other public spaces. Also the permission of opening driving, flying and boat schools is linked to the requirement of wearing a face mask. This was extended once more upon June 29th.

column14: On May 1, the prefects of Corsica announced that reinforced controls will be organized throughout the island, including the mobilization of nearly 600 gendarmes and police officers every day, in an effort to increase compliance with lockdown restrictions in order to achieve the goal of a gradual exit from lockdown on May 11.

As of May 1, all of the island of Corsica is classified as green based on based on the active circulation of the virus and hospital pressure on resuscitation capacity within the region. The green color of the region will be used to determine the way in which deconfinement measures will be applied as the end of lockdown begins on May 11, as a broader deconfinement will be applied in green departments and more constraints and stricter action in red departments.

column14: On April 29th, the government of North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, announced that all non-essential services usually operating within a minimum distance of less than 1.5m, except from barbershops and foot care, were prohibited, starting on May 4th.

Non-essential shops (*) larger than 800 m2 have to remain closed. For smaller non-essential shops, the number of customers allowed inside the shop is limited to 1 person per 10 m2. For vehicle businesses, bicycle shops and book shops, the limitations on the number of customers hold as well, but not the 800 m2 rule. These can open even if larger than 800 m2.
Malls have to develop and implement a hygiene and municipalities have the responsibility to manage the pedestrian traffic in pedestrian zones and other shopping streets, e.g. by limiting access.

(*) all other than: food and feed shops, weekly markets, pick up and delivery services, beverage shops, pharmacies, health care supply stores, drug stores, petrol stations, banks, post offices, cleaning services, laundry services, newspaper shops, hardware shops, gardening businesses, animal need, food offers for the needy, or retail markets.

In the German state of Saarland, the principle of social distancing applies: Contact with other people should be restricted to the absolute minimum necessary. Try to have contact with as few people as possible and always with the same group of people. Whenever possible, keep a minimum distance of one and a half meters from other people.

This excludes contact with members of your own household, spouses, life partners, civil union partners, relatives in the direct line of descent, brothers and sisters, nephews and nieces, and members of their respective households (designated family circle).

In the case of private gatherings in enclosed spaces at home, it is essential to apply hygiene and social distancing rules, to limit the number of people so as to be able to observe the 1.5-meter social distancing rule and to ensure sufficient ventilation. If possible, private gatherings should take place outdoors.

In Switzerland, the canton Aargau decided that from the 11th of May on Aargau will lift the basic ban on visits and introduce a controlled right to visit.
Visitors must log in and register for traceability. A health checklist must also be completed. The visit must take place in controlled and protected meeting areas. The management of the institution defines the exact framework in the form of a visitation concept.

Visits to acute hospitals are still prohibited. In certain cases the management can authorize visits. Publicly accessible restaurants or cafeterias of acute hospitals remain closed to outside parties while the ones of the psychiatries and nursing homes are allowed to open with a protection concept. Psychiatries allow controlled visits.

Rehabilitation clinics and nursing homes allow controlled visit if the clinic/ home management considers relaxation based on the patient population and the current situation to be justifiable. Otherwise the regulation applies analogously to the acute hospitals.
The publicly accessible restaurants or cafeterias are allowed to open with a protection concept, provided that the rehabilitation clinic management considers the opening to be reasonable due to the patient population and the current situation.

On June 6th, 2020, the Swiss canton of Appenzell Innerrhoden has further lifted the original restriction on visits to hospitals, elderly homes, and facilities for people with disabilities. Visits do not longer need to be pre-registered, however, all visitors need to register at the entrance, record their personal information, and verify that they do not show any Covid-19 symptoms. Public cafeterias and restaurants within the facilities are allowed to reopen under the condition that they meet the general health advice and guarantee for social distance.

As of June 7, 2020 Lower Saxony (Germany) orders persons who return to their place of residence in Lower Saxony after a stay in Sweden to go into 14-day quarantine. This was announced by the Lower Saxony Ministry for Social Affairs, Health and Equality. Sweden has exceeded the so-called incidence of 50 infected persons per 100,000 inhabitants during the weekend, which is the decisive factor for the regulation.

For businesses/institutions to be allowed to open, special hygiene concepts have to be developed. This includes:
-	Restaurants, bars etc.
-	Providers of accommodation
-	All places open to the public (shops etc.)
-	Zoos
-	Playgrounds
-	Inside leisure activities and inside sports
-       swimming pools and amusement parks (since 8.6., before they were closed)
These hygiene concepts regularly include the limitation of visitors/customers, maintaining the distance of 1,5m, regulation of movement, frequent disinfection of surfaces regularly touched by visitors/customers, frequent cleaning of sanitary areas, and regular air circulation.
For the following businesses/activities (and possibly others as well), contact data of visitors/customers has to be sored for six weeks and to be handed out to the responsible public office on request:
-	Restaurants, bars etc.
-	Providers of accommodation
-	Inside leisure activities and inside sports (including religious events since 9.8.)

As of June 8, 2020 Lower Saxony (Germany), allows cultural events outdoors with less than 250 persons and exclusively as a seating event and with restrictions ( Distance, Access management, contact data acquisition). Other Events remain prohibited. This policy is in place until June 22, 2020.
As of June 8, 2020 Lower Saxony (Germany), extends wedding celebrations/ funerals to  50 persons (while maintaining the distance rule however) until further notice.
Night clubs have to remain closed

As of June 8, the Mecklenburg-Vorpommern Ministry of Health state that people who come back to their place of residence in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern after a stay in Sweden have to quarantine for 14 days in their own home or in another suitable accommodation.
Brothels have to remain closed. The provision of sexual services remains prohibited.

Events larger than 250 persons are banned. Requirements are a hygiene concept, no open buffets, no dancing and no activities with an increased emission of droplets such as singing or the use of air instruments. Only solo performances are allowed with distance to the spectators.
Events in the public space with group activities where participants are not seated at for most of the time and where participants remain the same may only be held outside and not exceed 50 persons. Contact data has to be collected.
Markets/fairs… in the public may only be helf outside and not exceed 100 persons at a time. Alcohol may not be served. Weekly markets are not affected by these rules.
Events where participants are seated most of the time such as concerts, lectures, or cinemas may not exceed 250 people outside and 100 inside. Contact data of participants has to be stored.
Events in private houses are not allowed if they exceed the general social distancing rules 
These rules do not hold for events necessary for the public safety and order, legislation, social security, or for events necessary for business reasons, or exams, or care work, or elections.

Germany is enforcing a Restriction of Non-Essential Businesses: The Bavarian government has prohibited the operation of all leisure facilities such as swimming baths, cinemas, bars and discotheques, theatres, museums, sports grounds and playgrounds, but also brothels and restaurants of all kinds. Exceptions are company canteens and the serving of take-away food or delivery. It must be ensured that the distance between guests is at least 1.5 metres and that there are no more than 30 people in the rooms. It was also prohibited to open retail shops of any kind, with the exception in particular of food and beverage shops, pharmacies and banks, post offices and online shops.
According to Prime Minister Markus Söder, outdoor pools - not indoor pools - are allowed to reopen on June 8, as well as gyms, dance schools and rehabilitation facilities.

The government of Schleswig-Holstein announced that it will spend 5 Million Euro on a testing strategy. Additionally to routine testing of patients with symptoms, random tests will be carried out at schools and kindergartens, and nursing homes, and in the tourism sector for better tracking of infections. Also, special teams shall be sent to schools with positive cases. These teams shall quickly test all contact persons of infected students.

As of June 13, Thuringia implements new guidelines regarding non-essential business. Concert halls, orchestral and theatrical performances and cinemas in closed rooms follow the basic infection protection measures, a controllable entry, and exit, and participation must only be guaranteed in seats. State-sponsored theaters and orchestras will be closed until 31 of August. Indoor pools, adventure pools, saunas, or thermal baths can open again but must obtain written approval from the responsible district or city. Restaurants must track their customers. Trade fairs, exhibitions, and special markets are permitted if prior written permission has been obtained from the responsible district or city. Discos, brothels, and clubs are closed.

On May 12th, 2020, the government of Thuringia, Germany, announced that restriction to behavior in public places whereas 1.5m distance is to be held at all times. The original social distancing policy did not allow people to meet outside; now, two families or two common households are allowed to meet. Also, starting April 24th, all residents are required to wear a mask on the premises of shopping centers, public transport, and research facilities. As of June 13, 2020, there is no longer a legally binding contact restriction in Thuringia, but all people are still advised to keep physical and social contact with other people as low as possible. Wherever it is reasonable, the distance rules (1,5m) remains.  It is recommended that people meet no more than ten other people. Mask requirement also remains in public transportation and shopping premises.

Thuringia will resume face-to-face classes for individual student groups for the high school graduates from April 27, 2020. From May 4, 2020, the final classes of elementary schools, regular schools, community schools, and vocational schools as well as the degrees of special schools will follow. By June 2, 2020, all schools will offer face-to-face classes in different versions. Daycare for children will also gradually reopen in May 2020. With the new regulation, from June 15th onwards, there will be a daily childcare offer for all children. Emergency care is ended. From class five onwards, the change between distance and classroom instruction remains. The distance rules apply to all students from the fifth grade. Kindergarten and after-school care are guaranteed for the summer holidays. From August 31st - as far as the infection situation allows - school lessons should run completely normal again.

As of June 13, Thuringia announced a relaxation of the policy of restriction on all kinds of gatherings in public spaces, open-air, and buildings. Private celebrations such as family celebrations, birthdays, and weddings are possible again. If there are more than 30 people in closed rooms and more than 75 people in the open air, the event must be reported to the responsible district or city. This must be done 48 hours in advance. Appropriate infection control precautions must be taken, and contact tracking ensured. The organizer is responsible for this.
Outdoor demonstrations are possible without restrictions on the number of participants. Still, public, village, city, marksmen or wine festivals, sporting events with spectators, festivals, funfair, and similar, public, free, or accessible events are generally prohibited.

column14: On May 12th, 2020, the government of Thuringia, Germany, announced a relaxation policy of restriction on all kinds of gatherings in public spaces or buildings. Local electoral committees, assembly meetings, trade unions, professional associations meetings, institutions that perform public law tasks, including the necessary training, further education, and training, are permitted indoors in compliance with infection protection law. Gatherings or meetings that serve religious purposes, including religious and non-religious funerals and marriages, provided that no notification is required. The theaters and orchestras, which are institutionally funded by the state and public events such as folk, village, city, shooting or wine festivals, sporting events with spectators, festivals, funfair, and similar events are prohibited until the end of August 31, 2020. In Germany the State of Baden-Wuerttemberg is enforcing a two-week quarantine on all people that want to travel to the state after April 11.
It ends on July 14.

As of May 26, 2020, persons entering Thuringia from a state outside the member states of the European Union as well as from Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, Switzerland, Great Britain, and Northern Ireland are obliged to go directly to their own apartment or other accommodation immediately after entry. They have to stay in domestic quarantine there for 14 days. Exceptions for domestic quarantine if a person works in the health system, public security and order, the maintenance of diplomatic and consular relations, the functionality of the legal system, the functionality of representatives of the people, government, and administration of the federal government, the countries and municipalities. The functionality of the organs of the European Union and international organizations who have stayed outside of Germany as part of their work as an employee of air, ship, rail, or bus transport companies or as a crew of airplanes, ships, trains, and buses are also an exception.

The original quarantine policy was targeted states outside the member state of the EU as well as from Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, Switzerland, Great Britain, and Northern Ireland; as of June 15, 2020, people who enter Thuringia by land, sea or air from abroad and who have been in a risk area within 14 days prior to entry are obliged to go directly to their own home or other suitable accommodation and to separate themselves there for 14 days after their entry.

column14: On June 16, the test strategy is expanded. People arriving in hospitals / care facilities / initial take-up places or people in schools with suspected cases should be tested for SARS-CoV-2.
On June 16 the Berlin government has quarantined 13 apartment buildings in the Berlin-Neukölln district after 57 people were confirmed to have contracted coronavirus in the area.

As of June 15, 2020, people who enter Thuringia by land, sea or air from abroad and who have been in a risk area within 14 days prior to entry are obliged to go directly to their own home or other suitable accommodation and to separate themselves there for 14 days after their entry. The risk area is classified by the Federal Ministry of Health, the Federal Foreign Office and the Federal Ministry of the Interior and published by the Robert Koch Institute.
Exceptions for domestic quarantine: if a person works in the health system, public security and order, the maintenance of diplomatic and consular relations, the functionality of the legal system, the functionality of representatives of the people, government, and administration of the federal government, the countries and municipalities. The functionality of the organs of the European Union, international organizations, and members of the armed forces who have stayed outside of Germany as part of their work as an employee of air, ship, rail, or bus transport companies or as a crew of airplanes, ships, trains, and buses are also an exception. column14:
For businesses/institutions to be allowed to open, special hygiene concepts have to be developed. This includes:
-	Restaurants, bars etc.
-	Providers of accommodation
-	All places open to the public (shops etc.)
-	Zoos
-	Playgrounds
-	Inside leisure activities and inside sports
-       swimming pools and amusement parks (since 8.6., before they were closed)
These hygiene concepts regularly include the limitation of visitors/customers, maintaining the distance of 1,5m, regulation of movement, frequent disinfection of surfaces regularly touched by visitors/customers, frequent cleaning of sanitary areas, and regular air circulation.
For the following businesses/activities (and possibly others as well), contact data of visitors/customers has to be sored for six weeks and to be handed out to the responsible public office on request:
-	Restaurants, bars etc.
-	Providers of accommodation
-	Inside leisure activities and inside sports (including religious events since 9.8.)
From 29.6. on, private events are allowed for up to 50 people if contact data is stored and hygiene requirements are met as for organised events (no dancing, no open buffets, hygiene concept…)
Night clubs have to remain closed
Brothels have to remain closed. The provision of sexual services remains prohibited.
As of June 29, the government of Berlin decided to allow symptom-free employees of all day care centers in Berlin to be tested for the Coronavirus.
Service providers such as barbers may only work on a client’s face if special measures to prevent infection are taken.

Germany is enforcing a Restriction of Non-Essential Businesses: The Bavarian government has prohibited the operation of all leisure facilities such as swimming baths, cinemas, bars and discotheques, theatres, museums, sports grounds and playgrounds, but also brothels and restaurants of all kinds. Exceptions are company canteens and the serving of take-away food or delivery. It must be ensured that the distance between guests is at least 1.5 metres and that there are no more than 30 people in the rooms. It was also prohibited to open retail shops of any kind, with the exception in particular of food and beverage shops, pharmacies and banks, post offices and online shops.
Previously, an area of 20 square metres per person was mandatory in public institutions. From June 29 onwards, 10 sqm per person will be enough. This applies above all to customer traffic in shops, but also to leisure and cultural facilities such as museums or zoological institutions.
